    <h1>How to Work with Git + GitHub</h1>
    <p>
      This guide is for first-time developers working on real team projects. It teaches the
      <strong>minimum Git skills</strong> to work safely, collaborate smoothly, and ship features
      through <strong>GitHub Pull Requests</strong>.
    </p>

    <!-- Section 1: Git Concepts -->
    <h2>1) Git Concepts (Short Mental Model)</h2>

    <h3>The Flow (Memorize This)</h3>
    <p class="flow-diagram">
      <strong>Remote GitHub repo</strong> → clone → <strong>local repo</strong> → create <strong>branch</strong>
      → edit files → stage → commit → push → open <strong>PR</strong> → review → merge
    </p>

    <h3>Key Terms (Plain Language)</h3>

    <h4>Repo (Repository)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A folder that Git tracks: it contains your code + full change history.</li>
      <li>You have:
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Local repo</strong> (on your computer)</li>
          <li><strong>Remote repo</strong> (<code>origin</code> on GitHub)</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Commit History</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A timeline of "snapshots" of the code.</li>
      <li>Each commit has a message and represents a logical change.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Branch</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A branch is a <strong>separate line of work</strong>.</li>
      <li>Think of it as a <strong>pointer to a series of commits</strong>.</li>
      <li>You create a branch to build a feature safely without breaking <code>main</code>.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Working Directory vs Staging Area</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Working directory</strong> = your actual files as you edit them.</li>
      <li><strong>Staging area</strong> = changes you've selected to be included in the next commit.</li>
    </ul>

    <h4>Pull Request (PR)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>A PR is how you ask to merge your branch into a <strong>parent branch</strong> (usually <code>main</code>).</li>
      <li>PRs exist so the team can:
        <ul>
          <li>Review your code</li>
          <li>Run tests/CI</li>
          <li>Catch issues early</li>
          <li>Keep <code>main</code> stable</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Section 2: Core Commands -->
    <h2>2) Core Commands (Minimum Set)</h2>
    <p class="tip-box">Use these. You don't need anything else to start.</p>

    <h3><code>git clone</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Downloads a remote repo to your computer.</p>
    <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/org/project.git</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git status</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Shows what changed and what's staged.</p>
    <pre><code>git status</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git checkout -b &lt;branch&gt;</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Creates a new branch and switches to it.</p>
    <pre><code>git checkout -b feature/login-ui
# OR
git switch -c feature/login-ui</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git add</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Stages changes for the next commit.</p>
    <pre><code>git add .
# OR stage a single file:
git add src/app.js</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git commit -m</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Saves a snapshot of staged changes with a message.</p>
    <pre><code>git commit -m "Add login form validation"</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git push -u origin &lt;branch&gt;</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Uploads your branch to GitHub (remote = <code>origin</code>).</p>
    <pre><code>git push -u origin feature/login-ui</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git pull --rebase</code></h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Brings latest changes from remote and replays your commits on top (cleaner history).</p>
    <pre><code>git pull --rebase</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git log --oneline</code> (recommended)</h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Shows recent commits in a compact way.</p>
    <pre><code>git log --oneline</code></pre>

    <h3><code>git diff</code> (recommended)</h3>
    <p><strong>What it does:</strong> Shows what changed before you commit.</p>
    <pre><code>git diff</code></pre>

    <!-- Section 3: Real Workflow -->
    <h2>3) The Real Workflow (What You Do Every Time)</h2>

    <h3>Scenario A: Starting a New Feature (Standard Flow)</h3>

    <div class="checklist-box">
      <h4>Daily Workflow Checklist</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Update local <code>main</code></li>
        <li>Create a dedicated branch</li>
        <li>Implement changes</li>
        <li>Stage + commit</li>
        <li>Stay synced with parent branch</li>
        <li>Push branch</li>
        <li>Open PR</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h4>Commands (Copy-Paste)</h4>
    <pre><code># 1) Go to main and sync it
git checkout main
git pull --rebase

# 2) Create your feature branch from main
git checkout -b feature/&lt;short-name&gt;

# 3) Work on code (edit files)

# 4) Check and stage
git status
git diff
git add .

# 5) Commit
git commit -m "Describe the change clearly"

# 6) Push your branch
git push -u origin feature/&lt;short-name&gt;</code></pre>

    <p>Then open a PR on GitHub:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>base: <code>main</code></li>
      <li>compare: <code>feature/&lt;short-name&gt;</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Scenario B: Fixing Something on an Existing Feature Branch</h3>

    <p class="tip-box"><strong>The Rule:</strong> Branch from the branch you want to merge into. That branch is your <strong>parent branch</strong>.</p>

    <h4>When to Branch from <code>main</code></h4>
    <p>Branch from <code>main</code> when your work will be merged into <code>main</code>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>You're building a brand-new feature</li>
      <li>You're fixing a bug that affects production behavior</li>
    </ul>
    <pre><code>git checkout main
git pull --rebase
git checkout -b feature/user-settings</code></pre>

    <h4>When to Branch from an Existing Feature Branch</h4>
    <p>Branch from a feature branch when your work will be merged into that feature branch (not into <code>main</code> yet).</p>

    <p><strong>Example 1:</strong> Quick UI fix for another teammate's branch</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Parent branch: <code>feature/onboarding-flow</code></li>
      <li>Your branch: <code>bugfix/onboarding-button-align</code></li>
    </ul>
    <pre><code>git checkout feature/onboarding-flow
git pull --rebase
git checkout -b bugfix/onboarding-button-align</code></pre>

    <p><strong>Example 2:</strong> Add tests to a feature that's not ready for main</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Parent branch: <code>feature/payments</code></li>
      <li>Your branch: <code>test/payments-api</code></li>
    </ul>
    <pre><code>git checkout feature/payments
git pull --rebase
git checkout -b test/payments-api</code></pre>

    <!-- Section 4: Best Practices -->
    <h2>4) Branching Best Practices (Team Rules)</h2>

    <h3>Branch Rules</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Never work directly on <code>main</code></strong></li>
      <li><strong>One branch per task:</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Feature work → <code>feature/...</code></li>
          <li>Bug fix → <code>bugfix/...</code></li>
          <li>Urgent production fix → <code>hotfix/...</code></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Branch Naming Examples</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><code>feature/login-ui</code></li>
      <li><code>bugfix/null-check-orders</code></li>
      <li><code>hotfix/prod-crash</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Commit Rules</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Make commits <strong>small and meaningful</strong></li>
      <li>Prefer <strong>several small commits</strong> over one giant commit</li>
      <li>A good commit answers: "What did I change?"</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Section 5: PR Checklist -->
    <h2>5) PR Ready Checklist (Do This Every Time)</h2>
    <p>Before you open a PR, verify this list.</p>

    <div class="checklist-box">
      <h4>Code + Sync</h4>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>My branch is based on the correct <strong>parent branch</strong></li>
        <li>I pulled latest changes from parent branch</li>
        <li>I resolved conflicts locally (if any)</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>Quality</h4>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>I ran tests relevant to my change</li>
        <li>The project builds / runs locally</li>
        <li>No debug prints / commented junk code</li>
        <li>Formatting / linting is clean (if applicable)</li>
        <li>I updated docs/readme if needed</li>
      </ul>

      <h4>PR Content</h4>
      <ul class="checklist">
        <li>PR is small enough to review (not 2,000 lines unless unavoidable)</li>
        <li>PR description includes: what changed, why, how to test, screenshots (if UI)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- Section 6: Good PR Standard -->
    <h2>6) The "Good PR" Standard</h2>

    <h3>Good PR Title Examples</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><code>Feature: Add login form validation</code></li>
      <li><code>Bugfix: Prevent crash when orders list is empty</code></li>
      <li><code>Hotfix: Fix production crash on startup</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>PR Description Template (Copy-Paste)</h3>
    <pre><code><strong>What changed</strong>
- (bullet list of changes)

<strong>Why</strong>
- (1-2 sentences: the problem + reason for approach)

<strong>How to test</strong>
1. (step 1)
2. (step 2)
3. Expected result: (what should happen)

<strong>Screenshots / Notes</strong>
- (UI screenshots or anything reviewers should know)</code></pre>

    <h3>Good Commit Message Examples</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><code>Add validation for email input</code></li>
      <li><code>Fix null pointer in order summary</code></li>
      <li><code>Add unit tests for pricing logic</code></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Bad Commit Messages (Avoid)</h3>
    <ul class="avoid-list">
      <li><code>fix</code></li>
      <li><code>changes</code></li>
      <li><code>update stuff</code></li>
      <li><code>wip</code></li>
      <li><code>final</code></li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Section 7: Troubleshooting -->
    <h2>7) When Things Go Wrong (Common Fixes)</h2>

    <h3>Case 1: "My push was rejected because remote has new commits"</h3>
    <p>This usually means someone updated the branch on GitHub and your local branch is behind.</p>
    <p><strong>Safe fix:</strong></p>
    <pre><code>git pull --rebase
git push</code></pre>
    <p>If you get conflicts during rebase: fix conflicts in files, then continue. If needed, ask for help (rebasing can be tricky the first time).</p>

    <h3>Case 2: "I opened a PR to the wrong branch"</h3>
    <p>Example: you opened PR into <code>main</code> but it should go into <code>feature/payments</code>.</p>
    <p><strong>Safe fix:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li>On GitHub: <strong>Edit PR</strong></li>
      <li>Change the <strong>base branch</strong> from <code>main</code> → correct parent branch</li>
      <li>No code changes required.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Case 3: "I accidentally committed to main"</h3>
    <p>Stop immediately. Do not push.</p>
    <p><strong>Safe fix (if you haven't pushed yet):</strong></p>
    <pre><code># Create a feature branch containing your commit
git checkout -b feature/move-accidental-main-work

# Go back to main and reset it to remote state
git checkout main
git pull --rebase</code></pre>
    <p>Then push the branch and open a PR normally:</p>
    <pre><code>git push -u origin feature/move-accidental-main-work</code></pre>

    <!-- Quick Summary -->
    <h2>Quick "Do / Don't" Summary</h2>

    <div class="do-dont-grid">
      <div class="do-box">
        <h4>Do</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Always branch before coding</li>
          <li>Commit small, clear changes</li>
          <li>Sync with parent branch regularly</li>
          <li>Open PRs early (even as drafts)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="dont-box">
        <h4>Don't</h4>
        <ul>
          <li>Don't develop directly on <code>main</code></li>
          <li>Don't open PRs without testing</li>
          <li>Don't dump giant PRs unless unavoidable</li>
          <li>Don't "fix conflicts on GitHub" if you can avoid it—fix locally</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

